==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Saker
<hw>Sa"ker</hw> <pr>(s⟦amac⟧"k⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>sacre</ets> (cf. It. <ets>sagro</ets>, Sp. & Pg. <ets>sacre</ets>),
either fr. L. <ets>sacer</ets> sacred, holy, as a translation of Gr.
<grk>"ie`rax</grk> falcon, from <grk>"iero`s</grk> holy, or more
probably from Ar. <ets>⟦cced⟧aqr</ets> hawk.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>sacar</asp>, <asp>sacre</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A falcon (<spn>Falco sacer</spn>)
native of Southern Europe and Asia, closely resembling the
lanner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The female is called <stype>chargh</stype>, and the male
<stype>charghela</stype>, or <stype>sakeret</stype>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>The peregrine falcon.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A small piece of artillery.</def>
<rj><au>Wilhelm.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On the bastions were planted culverins and <qex>sakers</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The culverins and <qex>sakers</qex> showing their deadly muzzles
over the rampart.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sakeret</ent>⟦br⟧
